  "prompt": "What is the difference between clause and provision?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the differences between a clause and a provision:\n\nClause:\n1. A specific section or paragraph within a legal document\n2. Generally shorter and more focused on a single specific point\n3. Often part of a larger document like a contract or treaty\n4. Typically deals with a particular aspect or detail\n5. Can be a component of a broader provision\n\nProvision:\n1. A broader statement or requirement in a legal document\n2. Usually more comprehensive and covers a wider scope\n3. Can contain multiple clauses\n4. Describes a substantive rule, condition, or requirement\n5. Often addresses overall rights, obligations, or guidelines\n6. More general and encompassing in nature\n\nExample:\nIn a rental agreement:\n- A clause might specify the exact rent amount\n- A provision might cover the entire rental terms, including payment conditions, maintenance responsibilities, and termination rules\n\nIn summary, a clause is a smaller, more specific part of a document, while a provision is a broader, more comprehensive rule or statement that may include multiple clauses.",
